LeetCode 1: Two Sum requires Java code returning indices of two distinct elements in nums summing to target. Exactly one solution exists per constraints.

Java Implementation:-
class Solution {
    public int[] twoSum(int[] nums, int target) {
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> seen = new HashMap<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
            int complement = target - nums[i];
            if (seen.containsKey(complement)) {
                return new int[]{seen.get(complement), i};
            }
            seen.put(nums[i], i);
        }
        return new int[]{}; // Unreachable per constraints
    }
}

This O(n) time, O(n) space solution uses HashMap for constant-time lookups.
​

Thought Process
Brute force double loop checks pairs in O(n²), viable for n≤10^4 but inefficient. HashMap trades space for time: store index of each number seen so far, query for complement before adding current.
Order matters: check complement first prevents self-pairing (e.g., nums[i]+nums[i]=target wrongly). Overwriting indices for duplicates fine since constraints guarantee unique solution pair.
Java specifics: HashMap<Integer, Integer> maps value to latest index. int[] return type matches signature. No null/empty handling needed per constraints.
​

Step-by-Step Logic
Create HashMap<Integer, Integer> seen to store number → index.
Loop i from 0 to nums.length - 1.
Calculate complement = target - nums[i].
if (seen.containsKey(complement)) return {seen.get(complement), i}.
seen.put(nums[i], i) (overwrites if duplicate).
Return empty array (unreachable).
​

Edge Cases
Array length 2: [3,3] target 6: i=0 stores 3→0; i=1 complement=3 found, returns.
Duplicates mid-array: [3,2,3] target 6: First 3→0; skip 2; second 3 complement=3 finds prior index.
Negatives/overflow: [-1,2147483647] target 2147483646: Java int handles -2^31 to 2^31-1; complement safe.
Zero target: [0,0] returns; [1,-1] returns indices summing to 0.
All same value: Constraints imply target=2*value, indices or similar.
Large n=10^4: HashMap scales; no resize issues in practice.
